text: Seems I cant send videos here :(
But now his anatomy is more realistic, as before his abs were looking way too chiseled :joy:
So that's that guy, he's titled "Vessel", concept by Dhenzel Obeng
That is excellent, Marceli! and yes the latest version is much correct.
so you sculpted it from scratch or used a base mesh?
The human body was from a base mesh, and the creature was from scratch of course :)
yeah I mean the human :wink:
the pose of fingers are looking great , too
do you have topologies for all of those meshes, I mean you rendered with displacement maps or directly rendered in Zbrush?
if rendered with maps, whic software you used?

Aww thank you :blush: yeah I wanted him to seem like he was sort of contorting or in pain since he's got a massive parasite type creature on him :stuck_out_tongue_closed_eyes: I can send you the topology of the model in a bit, currently sending the pics i have saved on my phone haha
Like I said, sculpted in Zbrush, Retopo in Maya, Textured in Substance Painter and Rendered using Arnold :)
Perfect. I think it only needs to have a similar lighting to the concept, if this version is not your approach on purpose.
Currently dont have displacement set up on him, it's just all bump map
or normal map?
Yes bump map as in Normal map

And the lighting is just a quick thing I threw together. I was going to the Move Summit in Edinburgh and wanted to have it rendered so I could show it and get feedback from people. Final lighting will get tweaked to be either more like the concept or go in a wholly different direction :)
so could you go there in Feb? got feedback?
good piece of work it is. I am sure the concept owner liked to see it modeled!

Yeah lots of us went from our course. I got feedback from a bunch of people from AXIS animation. I also have a mentorship there, I usually go to their Glasgow studio every friday, but of course now I cant :upside_down_face:
that's an incredible chance(or was and hopefully to be)!
But that's how I got the feedback about the saturation of the guts vs the face. So I already made that tweak so the focal point is the face. I'll find a comparison I rendered quickly :)

Yeah it's really great. They tend to hire mentees after they graduate, so I hope that I can get a job at Axis at some point. Hopefully I get to go back to the mentorship soon too :joy: but I do get email feedback from my Axis mentor now and then. They're all just busy with the change of working from home I guess
That's good they keep sending feedback. Are there many options other than Axis? I am not very informed about the vfx capacity of your area.
So being a freelancer is your another aim?

Axis is the only real place I'd like to work in Scotland. If not Axis, then I'd move down to England, most likely London, if I could get a job somewhere like ILM or DNEG or Framestore etc. Theres also plenty of video game companies around England. A big one I'm a fan of is Creative Assembly who make the Total War game series

I'm not really aiming to be a freelancer at the moment, because I know nothing about how it's done and I figure that I need experience first in order to be able to get hired as a freelancer. They have to know that I'm capable of doing the work myself correctly, whereas currently I want to get a job in a studio so I can learn loads from other people. But in the future, once I'm a bit more experienced, if having a job means going freelance I would not mind that! It's just I dont know how it really works, with finding jobs and what it's like working as a freelancer and also having to do your own taxes etc

You are right about getting experienced by working as in-house. Apart from how much talented you are, getting experienced is mostly about being involved in a team work, tight deadlines, learning the quickest ways to solve a problem in a short time, realising how your department is in relation with other departments(causes and effects) and dealing with client's (sometimes) extreme demands. Those teach a lot and when you become a freelancer, you are expected to know and be prepared for all those stuff. Also the company you worked for permanently is possible to become your first client as a freelancer.
I am a freelancer too, after about 8 years of permanent working. Of course it does not have to be that long but what I find attractive about being an inhouse(perm) artist is to be a part of a collective mind/team as soon as we are happy with our works because freelance jobs are usually short term projects where you are expected to serve your skill and than go back to home :slightly_smiling_face:

Yeah exactly I also love being in a team and learning from other people and just the constant interaction so that I know what the next person in the pipeline needs from me. So I definitely want to experience a real studio first and then maybe in the future freelance opportunities can open up :grin:
Hopefully :slightly_smiling_face:
very good!
so you like dealing with ornaments and detailed works like that
I mostly worked on the gold material as it's the focus. Most of the other materials are just default materials or smart materials just to get the general look while I continue working on it all
I do but it's also kinda exhausting. Afterwards I want to do a bit of a simpler project
:slightly_smiling_face: I can imagine

Marceli, now I need to take a step from the computer. I will catch you later, ok? Meanwhile when you access your computer, please also share the topologies of the characters of your work with me. I will be looking forward to that.
Before I go, congrats for your hardwork and discipline!
No worries! I'll send stuff here and you can just have a look when you're available :blush:
Thank you! Much to do but enjoying it all a lot. Enjoy the rest of your day :grin:
You too, Marceli! Chat with you soon.
this portrait was a brief set by AXIS to get onto the mentorship, which i got a space on :slightly_smiling_face:
This portrait is beautiful!
Well, I am sending you my notes like you did, in psd.

<https://www.hippydrome.com/>
And this is a great topology knowledge page where I check out for my characters.
The more you learn about topology approaches, the more flexible will be your topologies.
